"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-paris-2024-olympics-team-sa-updated-medal-tally-simbine-heroics\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbParis 2024: Team SA UPDATED medal tally after THOSE Akani Simbine heroics  Silver service.  Bayanda Walaza, Bradley Nkoana, Shaun Maswanganyi and Akani Simbine are all heroes after their scintillating display at the Paris 2024 Olympics. Here's the updated Team SA medal tally.  Bayanda Walaza, Bradley Nkoana, Shaun Maswanganyi and Akani Simbine have deservedly gotten their hands on silver at the Olympic Games after a sensational performance in the 4x100m relay final. Akani Simbine had a bit of work to do in the final leg after an immensely competitive race, but the 30-year-old got it done and finally laid his hands on some much-deserved silverware on the biggest stage. That must taste sweet for a man who's made the solo 100m final at three consecutive Olympic Games but narrowly missed out on the podium each time. Less than a week ago, he lost out on a medal by one-hundredth of a second in the biggest race in world sprinting. It was the fastest event of its type in history.  Tatjana Smith became the most decorated Olympian in South African history with her haul oftwo medalsin Paris. She claimed gold in the 100m breaststroke and silver in the 200m event, an exact reversal of her antics in Tokyo. The other Team SA medallists in 2024 areAlan Hatherlywho\\u00a0won bronze in the men's Mountain Bike (MTB) cross-country race; South Africa's first Olympic cycling medal since 1956, some 68 years ago, and theRugby Sevens sidewho claimed bronze by beating Australia. The 4x100m relay side takes Team SA's totalmedal tally to FIVE.A gold, two silvers and two bronzes.  Gardeo Isaacs, Zakhiti Nene, Antonie Nortje and Lythe Pillay finished eighth in Round 1 in 3:03.19 and failed to qualify for the final. However, a post-race disqualification for Nigeria has handed Team SA a lifeline and passage into the4x400m relay final onSaturday 10 August at 21:00. There they will face Japan, Zambia, the United States, Belgium, Great Britain, France, Italy andLetsile Tebogo's Botswana.The newly-crowned 200m Olympic champion is the man of the moment and was a surprise late inclusion in their 4x400m relay team. Immediately they become strong contenders.  View the full schedule via the Paris 2024official website.  Let us know by clicking on the comment tab below this article or emailinginfo@thesouthafrican.com. Meanwhile, you can also send a WhatsApp to 060 011 021 1. Follow@TheSAnews on XandThe South African on Facebookfor your social fix.  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias. 